---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import ExploreTopics from "../components/ExploreTopics.astro";
import amyImage from "../assets/images/AMY2B pancreatic amylase gene.png";

const basePath = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.endsWith("/")
  ? import.meta.env.BASE_URL
  : `${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`;
const withBase = (path: string) => `${basePath}${path.replace(/^\/+/, "")}`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Genetic Diet - ANT 104">
  <header
    class="relative overflow-hidden bg-gradient-to-br from-paper via-white to-paper py-6 md:py-8"
  >
    <div
      class="pointer-events-none absolute top-0 left-0 w-64 h-64 bg-sage/5 rounded-full -translate-x-1/2 -translate-y-1/2"
    >
    </div>
    <div
      class="pointer-events-none absolute bottom-0 right-0 w-96 h-96 bg-terracotta/5 rounded-full translate-x-1/2 translate-y-1/2"
    >
    </div>
    <div class="relative z-10 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 text-center">
      <span
        class="inline-block px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-terracotta bg-terracotta/10 rounded-full mb-2"
        >Genetic Diet</span
      >
      <h1 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-ink mb-2 leading-tight">
        Genetic Diet Adaptations
      </h1>
    </div>
  </header>
  <main class="mx-auto px-4 py-3">
    <div
      class="prose-custom space-y-6 text-ink/85 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mx-auto"
    >
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">To Agriculture</h2>
      <p>
        Going from hunting to an agricultural life changed how humans and dogs
        fundamentally lived. Dogs used to help humans capture prey, but now the
        Neolithic dogs changed from their carnivorous diet, and began consuming
        plant-based starches. This change in diet was possible through new
        biological changes in genes.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">
        Genetic Adaptation: Starch Digestion
      </h2>
      <p>
        Wild wolves carried two copies of the AMY2B gene which helps digesting
        carbs. The newly domesticated dogs living in the new villages began
        mutating to have more of those genes, as well as other carb digesting
        genes to help them slowly function in this new era of agriculture.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">
        Scholarly Evidence:
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-ink/85">
        <blockquote
          class="border-l-4 border-terracotta pl-4 my-4 italic text-ink/70"
        >
          <p class="mb-2">
            "We narrow the plausible range for the date of initial dog domestication to an interval spanning 11–16 thousand years ago, predating the rise of agriculture. In light of this finding, we expand upon previous work regarding the increase in copy number of the amylase gene (AMY2B) in dogs, which is believed to have aided digestion of starch in agricultural refuse."
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm">(Freedman Abstract)</p>
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote
          class="border-l-4 border-terracotta pl-4 my-4 italic text-ink/70"
        >
          <p class="mb-2">
            "Dog domestication as accompanied by selection at three genes with
            key roles in starch digestion: AMY2B, MGAM and SGLT1. Our results
            show that adaptations that allowed the early ancestors of modern
            dogs to thrive on a diet rich in starch… constituted a crucial step
            in early dog domestication… development of agriculture catalysed the
            domestication of dogs"
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm">(Axelsson 363)</p>
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote
          class="border-l-4 border-terracotta pl-4 my-4 italic text-ink/70"
        >
          <p class="mb-2">
            "Selection for increased AMY2B copy number did not take place during
            the early stage of domestication… and did not become widespread
            until several thousand years after the first appearance of
            starch-rich agricultural lifestyles"
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm">(Bergström 557–564)</p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 mb-8 flex flex-col items-center max-w-5xl mx-auto">
      <Image
        src={amyImage}
        alt="AMY2B pancreatic amylase gene expansion copy number"
        class="rounded-lg shadow-md w-full"
        format="png"
      />
      <figcaption
        class="text-xs text-muted text-center mt-4 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl"
      >
        <em
          >Expansion of copy number in the AMY2B pancreatic amylase gene largely
          occurred after the transition to agriculture. Ancient dogs are plotted
          against their age, with blue color indicating dogs from likely
          hunter–gatherer human contexts. Bars denote 95% binomial confidence
          intervals around the ratio of the number of reads mapping to the copy
          number variable region to those mapping to control regions throughout
          the genome.(Bergström 557–564).</em
        >
      </figcaption>
    </div>

    <div
      class="prose-custom space-y-6 text-ink/85 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mx-auto"
    >
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">
        My Research Findings:
      </h2>
      <p>
        The data and figure shows definite trend relating to agriculture. The
        change from hunting to farming did not just change human civilization
        permanently, but it changed biological markers in our first domesticated
        animal. This change altered canines to adapt to the crops we grew.
      </p>
    </div>
  </main>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <ExploreTopics current="genomic-diet" />
    <div class="mt-12 pt-8 border-t border-walnut/10 text-center">
      <a
        href={withBase("/citations")}
        class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-md bg-terracotta px-5 py-3 text-sm font-semibold text-white no-underline shadow-sm transition-colors hover:bg-walnut hover:text-white"
      >
        View Citations
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
